# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: breadfruit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:breadfruit/achene] An **achene** (/əˈkiːn/; from Ancient Greek ἀ*(*a*)* 'privative' and χαίνειν*(*khaínein*)* 'to gape'), also sometimes called **akene** and occasionally **achenium** or **achenocarp**, is a type of simple dry fruit produced by many species of flowering plants.
[src:breadfruit/achene] Achenes are monocarpellate (formed from one carpel) and indehiscent (they do not open at maturity).
[src:breadfruit/achene] Achenes contain a single seed that nearly fills the pericarp, but does not adhere to it.
[src:breadfruit/achene] In many species, what is called the "seed" is an achene, a fruit containing the seed.
[src:breadfruit/achene] The seed-like appearance is owed to the hardening of the fruit wall (pericarp), which encloses the solitary seed so closely as to seem like a seed coat.
[src:breadfruit/achene] The fruits of buttercup, buckwheat, caraway, quinoa, amaranth, and cannabis are typical achenes.
[src:breadfruit/achene] The achenes of the strawberry are sometimes mistaken for seeds.
[src:breadfruit/achene] The strawberry is an accessory fruit with an aggregate of achenes on its outer surface, and what is eaten is accessory tissue.
[src:breadfruit/achene] A rose produces an aggregate of achene fruits that are encompassed within an expanded hypanthium, which is a structure where basal portions of the calyx, the corolla, and the stamens unite with the receptacle to form a cup-shaped tube.
[src:breadfruit/achene] A winged achene, as in maple, is called a samara.
[src:breadfruit/achene] Some achenes have accessory hair-like structures that cause them to tumble in the wind in a manner similar to a tumbleweed.
[src:breadfruit/achene] This type sometimes is called a tumble fruit or diaspore.
[src:breadfruit/achene] A caryopsis or grain is a type of fruit that closely resembles an achene, but differs in that the pericarp is fused to the thin seed coat in the grain.
[src:breadfruit/achene] An utricle is like an achene, but the fruit is bladder-like or inflated.
[src:breadfruit/achene] Fruits of sedges are sometimes considered achenes although their one-locule ovary is a compound ovary.
[src:breadfruit/achene] The fruit of the family Asteraceae is also so similar to an achene that it is often considered to be one, although it derives from a compound inferior ovary (with one locule).
[src:breadfruit/achene] A special term for the Asteraceae fruit is cypsela (plural cypselae or cypselas).
[src:breadfruit/achene] For example, the white-gray husks of a sunflower "seed" are the walls of the cypsela fruit.
[src:breadfruit/achene] Many cypselas (e.g. dandelion) have modified calyx tissue called pappi attached that functions in biological dispersal of the seed.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The **ackee** (***Blighia sapida***), also known as **ackee apple**, is a fruit of the Sapindaceae (soapberry) family, as are the lychee and the longan.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The scientific name honours Captain William Bligh who took the fruit from Jamaica to the Royal Botanic Gardens in Kew, England, in 1793.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The English common name is derived from the West African Akan-language name *akye fufo*.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Although having a long-held reputation as being poisonous with potential fatalities, the fruit arils are renowned as delicious when ripe, prepared properly, and cooked and are a feature of various Caribbean cuisines.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Ackee is the national fruit of Jamaica and is considered a delicacy.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Ackee is an evergreen tree that grows about 10 metres tall, with a short trunk and a dense crown.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The leaves are paripinnately, compound 15–30 centimetres (6–12 inches) long, with 6–10 elliptical to oblong leathery leaflets.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The inflorescences are fragrant, up to 20 cm long, with unisexual flowers that bloom during warm months.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Each flower has five greenish-white petals, which are fragrant.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The fruit is pear-shaped and has three lobes (two to four lobes are common).
[src:breadfruit/ackee] When it ripens it turns from green to a bright red to yellow-orange and splits open to reveal three large, shiny black seeds, each partly surrounded by soft, creamy or spongy, white to yellow flesh — the aril having a nut-like flavour and texture of scrambled eggs.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The tree can produce fruit throughout the year, although January–March and October–November are typically periods of fruit production.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] There are up to as many as forty-eight cultivars of ackee, which are grouped into either "butter" or "cheese" types.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The cheese type is pale yellow in colour and is more robust and finds use in the canning industry.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The butter type is deeper yellow in color, and is more delicate and better suited for certain cuisine.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Imported to Jamaica from West Africa before 1773, the use of ackee in Jamaican cuisine is prominent.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Ackee is the national fruit of Jamaica, while ackee and saltfish is the official national dish of Jamaica.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The ackee is allowed to open fully before picking in order to eliminate toxicity.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] When it has "yawned" or "smiled", the seeds are discarded and the fresh, firm arils are parboiled in salted water or milk, and may be fried in butter to create a dish.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] In Caribbean cooking, they may be cooked with codfish and vegetables, or may be added to stew, curry, soup or rice with seasonings.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Ackee contains a moderate amount of carbohydrates, protein, and fat, providing 51–58% of the dry weight of the arils as composed of fatty acids – linoleic, palmitic, and stearic acids.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The raw fruit is a rich source of vitamin C.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The ackee is prominently featured in the Jamaican mento-style folk song "Linstead Market".
[src:breadfruit/ackee] In the song, a market seller laments, "Carry mi ackee go a Linstead market.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The Beat's 1982 album *Special Beat Service* includes the song "Ackee 1-2-3".
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The unripened aril and the inedible portions of the fruit contain hypoglycin toxins including hypoglycin A and hypoglycin B, known as "soapberry toxins".
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Hypoglycin A is found in both the seeds and the arils, while hypoglycin B is found only in the seeds.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Minimal quantities of the toxin are found in the ripe arils.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] In the unripe fruit, depending on the season and exposure to the sun, the concentrations may be up to 10 to 100 times greater.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] These two molecules are converted in the body to methylenecyclopropylacetic acid (MCPA), and are toxic with potential lethality.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] MCPA and hypoglycin A inhibit several enzymes involved in the breakdown of acyl CoA compounds, often binding irreversibly to coenzyme A, carnitine and carnitine acyltransferase I and II, reducing their bioavailability and consequently inhibiting beta oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Glucose stores are consequently depleted leading to hypoglycemia, and to a condition called Jamaican vomiting sickness.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] These effects occur only when the unripe aril (or an inedible part of the fruit) is consumed.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Though ackee is used widely in traditional dishes, research on its potential hypoglycin toxicity has been sparse and preliminary, requiring evaluation in well-designed clinical research to better understand its pharmacology, food uses, and methods for detoxification.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] In 2011, it was found that as the fruit ripens, the seeds act as a sink whereby the hypoglycin A in the arils convert to hypoglycin B in the seeds.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] In other words, the seeds help in detoxifying the arils, bringing the concentration of hypoglycin A to a level that is generally safe for consumption.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] Ackee canned in brine is a commodity item and is used for export by Jamaica, Haiti and Belize.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] If propagated by seed, trees will begin to bear fruit in 3–4 years.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The fruit has various uses in West Africa and in rural areas of the Caribbean Islands, including use of its "soap" properties as a laundering agent or fish poison.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The fragrant flowers may be used as decoration or cologne, and the durable heartwood used for construction, pilings, oars, paddles and casks.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] In African traditional medicine, the ripe arils, leaves or bark were used to treat minor ailments.
[src:breadfruit/ackee] The seeds were formerly used as standardized weights for weighing gold dust, leading to the currency issued by Great Britain in the former colony of Gold Coast to be named the "Gold Coast ackey".
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:breadfruit/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:breadfruit/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] It is popular throughout West Africa, and goes by many names including **apio**, **ogoglo**, **ogogoro** (**Ogog'**), **VC10,** **Kill Me Quick**, **Efie Nipa, Kele, Kumepreko, Anferewoase, Apiatiti, Home Boy, Nana Drobo, One Touch** among others.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] It is also known as sapele water, kparaga, kai-kai, Sun gbalaja, egun inu igo meaning *The Masquerade in the Bottle*, push-me-push-you, and/or crim-kena, sonsé ("do you do it?" in Yoruba language).
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] In the Igbo language it is known as *Akpuru achia*.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Other Nigerian epithets include: *Udi Ogagan*, *Agbagba* Urhobo, as well *OHMS* (Our Home Made Stuff), *Iced Water*, *Push Me, I Push You* and *Craze man in the bottle*.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Ghanaian moonshine is referred to as akpeteshie.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] With British colonization of what became known as the Gold Coast, such local brewing was outlawed in the early 1930s.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Dotse about his life under British colonial rule: "Our contention was that the drink the white man brought is the same as ours.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The white men's contention was that ours was too strong...Before the white men came we were using akpeteshie.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] But when they came they banned it, probably because they wanted to make sales on their own liquor.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] When you had a visitor whom you knew very well, then you ordered that kpótomenui be brought.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The name "akpeteshie" was given to the drink with its prohibition: the word comes from the Ga language (*ape te shie*, the act of hiding) spoken in greater Accra and means *they are hiding*, referring to the secretive way in which non-European inhabitants were forced to consume the beverage.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Despite being outlawed, illicit spirits remained commonplace, with reports that even schoolboys were able to easily obtain akpeteshie through the 1930s.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Demand for akpeteshie and the profits to be made from its sale was enough to encourage the spread of sugar cane cultivation in the Anlo region of Ghana.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Distillation was legalized with decolonization and Ghanaian independence.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The first factory was established in the Volta Region, taking advantage of the area's supply of sugar cane plantations.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Ogogoro is distilled from the juice of Raffia palm trees.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] An incision is made in the trunk and a gourd placed outside it for collection, which is collected a day or two later.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] After extraction, the sap is boiled to form steam, which subsequently condenses and is collected for consumption.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is distilled from palm wine or sugarcane juice.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] This sweetened liquid or wine is first fermented in a large barrels, sometimes with the help of yeast.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] After this first stage of fermentation, fires are built under the barrels in order to bring the liquid to a boil and pass the resulting vapor through a copper pipe within cooling barrels, where it condenses and drips into sieved jars.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The boiled juice then undergoes a distillation.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The resulting spirit is between 40 and 50% alcohol by volume.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is not professionally bottled or sealed, but instead poured into unlabeled used bottles.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The spirit can be bought wholesale from a brewer or by the glass at boutiques and bars.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Although not professionally advertised, the drink is very popular.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] This is partially due to its price, which is lower than that of other professionally bottled or imported drinks.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Its relative cheapness makes it a drink associated more with the poor, but even those who can afford better quality are said to consume the spirit in secret.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The potency of the liquor heavily affects the bodily senses, providing a feeling likened to that of a knockout punch.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Practiced drinkers can be seen acknowledging receipt by blowing out air or pounding their chest.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] As drink and commodity, respectively, ogogoro carries substantial cultural and economic significance within Nigeria.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] It is an essential part of numerous religious and social ceremonies; Burutu (Ijaw) priests pour it onto the ground as offerings to contact their gods, while fathers of Nigerian brides use it as a libation by which they provide their official blessing to a wedding.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] The economic facets of ogogoro have been equally salient throughout recent Nigerian history.
[src:breadfruit/akpeteshie] Many poor Nigerian families homebrew the drink as a means of economic subsistence, many of whom sell shots of it on city street corners.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] It may have influence from Middle Eastern *kibbeh* due to the immigration of Levantine Arabs as well as Turkish people throughout Latin America.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] The dough surrounding the filling, the *masa*, is made primarily of green banana and grated *yautía* with an optional addition of squash.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] Green banana can be replaced with breadfruit, cassava, taro, green or yellow plantains or other arrowroots.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] Alcapurrias are generally seasoned with lard, annatto, garlic and salt.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] The annatto gives it a signature yellow-orange color.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] Annatto seeds are simmered in lard to release most of their color and flavor.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] Seeds are discarded and the tinted lard is then poured over the *masa*.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] The *masa* is refrigerated for several hours to achieve a solid consistency.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] Diced potatoes cooked with *picadillo* or corned beef are the most typical fillings; others include longaniza, blood sausage, braised meat, cheese, seafood and vegetables.
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] They can be deep-fried in lard or oil, or baked (*alcapurrias horneadas*).
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] When cooked, the fritter is "hot and brittle".
[src:breadfruit/alcapurria] Alcapurrias are served at kiosks and at fine restaurants as well.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] First described by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, the species' origin is unclear due to its spread by humans, but it can be found in many tropical rainforests and gallery forests.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Various parts of the plant have regional or cultural uses.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The candlenut tree grows to a height of up to 30 m (98 ft), with wide spreading or pendulous branches.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The leaves are pale green, simple, and ovate or heart-shaped on mature shoots, but may be three-, five-, or seven-lobed on saplings.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] They are up to 20 cm (8 in) long and 13 cm (5 in) wide and young leaves are densely clothed in rusty or cream stellate hairs.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Petioles measure up to 12.5 cm (5 in) long and stipules about 5 mm (1⁄4 in).
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The flowers are small; male flowers measure around 5 mm in diameter, female flowers about 9 mm.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The fruit is a drupe about 4–6 cm (1+1⁄2–2+1⁄4 in) in diameter with one or two lobes; each lobe has a single soft, white, oily kernel contained within a hard shell about 2 cm (3⁄4 in) in diameter.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] These nuts, upon germinating, produce cotyledons or seed leaves up to 9 cm (3.5 in) long by 5.5 cm (2.2 in) wide.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] This plant was first described by Carl Linnaeus in his *Species Plantarum* (1753) as *Jatropha moluccana*.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] It was renamed as *Aleurites moluccana* by Carl Ludwig Willdenow in an 1805 edition of *Species Plantarum*, but the ending was corrected to match the gender of the Latin genus *Aleurites moluccanus*.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] While there are many online references to the spelling "Aleurites moluccana", this is not accepted by botanical authorities such as the International Plant Names Index or the Germplasm Resources Information Network.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The genus name derives from the Ancient Greek ἄλευρον (*áleuron*), meaning "flour" or "meal", and refers to the new growth which appears to be dusted with flour.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The species epithet means "from the Moluccas".
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Its native range is impossible to establish precisely because of early spread by humans, and the tree is now distributed throughout the New and Old World tropics including the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, Papuasia, Queensland in Australia, and some islands of the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The candlenut was first domesticated on the islands of Southeast Asia.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Remains of harvested candlenuts have been recovered from archaeological sites in Timor and Morotai in eastern Indonesia, dated to around 13,000 and 11,000 BP, respectively.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Archaeological evidence of candlenut cultivation is also found in Neolithic sites of the Toalean culture in southern Sulawesi dated to around 3,700 to 2,300 BP.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Early Austronesian voyagers introduced candlenuts, as a canoe plant, widely across the Pacific islands; the trees became naturalized to high volcanic islands.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Australia the seeds are eaten by rodents, in particular the giant white-tailed rat.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The broken shells of the fruits are often found underneath the trees.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The larvae of the coleopteran *Agrianome fairmairei* feed on dead candlenut wood, and are considered a delicacy in New Caledonia.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Because the seeds contain saponin, phorbol, and toxalbumins, they are mildly toxic when raw, inducing a laxative effect.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Heat treatment reduces the toxicity of the protein component.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] While mildly toxic when raw, the nut is appreciated in many cultures once cooked or toasted.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Indonesian and Malaysian cuisine, it is commonly used in curries, and on the Indonesian island of Java, it is used to make a thick sauce that is eaten with vegetables and rice.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] A Hawaiian condiment known as *ʻinamona* is made from roasted kukui mixed into a paste with salt.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] *ʻInamona* is a key ingredient in traditional Hawaiian *poke*.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The kernel is the source of candlenut oil, which has no known toxicity and is not an irritant, even to the eyes.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In ancient Hawaiʻi, kukui fruits were burned to provide light.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The nuts were strung in a row on a palm leaf midrib, lit on one end, and burned one by one every fifteen minutes or so.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] This led to their use as a measure of time.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Hawaiians extracted the oil from the nut and burned it in a stone oil lamp called a *kukui hele po* (light, darkness goes) with a wick made of *kapa* cloth.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] A red-brown dye made from the inner bark was used on *kapa* and *aho* (*Touchardia latifolia* cordage).
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] A coating of kukui oil helped preserve *ʻupena* (fishing nets).
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The *nohona waʻa* (seats) and *pale* (gunwales) of *waʻa* (outrigger canoes) were made from the wood.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The trunk was sometimes used to make smaller canoes used for fishing.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The oil can often be found in Indonesian hair-care products.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Fiji, where the nut is called *sikeci*, the oil is used in cosmetic products.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Wealthier members of the Batak people have their coffins (Karo: *pelangkah*) made from the wood, carved in the shape of a boat whose bow is decorated with the carved head of a hornbill, a horse, or a mythical beast known as a singa.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In the Philippines, the fruit and tree are traditionally known as *lumbang*, after which Lumban, a lakeshore town in Laguna province, is named.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Before the intrusion of non-native species, it was frequently used as a property-line manager because its silvery underleaf makes the tree easy to distinguish from a distance.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In the state of Sabah, Malaysian Borneo, the Dusun tribes call the fruit *godou* and use it in tattoo-making as an optional ingredient for the ink.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] As recently as 1993 on the outlying islands of the kingdom of Tonga, candlenuts were chewed into sweet-scented emollient used during a traditional funerary ritual.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] They were used for making various sweet-smelling oils for the skin.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Australia, Aboriginal Australians used them for a variety of similar purposes.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Flores near Ende, it is called *kéloré* and used as a mordant for dyes with *Morinda citrifolia* (*mengkudu*).
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] On the island of Rapa Iti in the Austral Islands, fish hooks were carved from the endocarp of the candlenut as a result of lacking other suitable material.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] These fish hooks were quite small and were used for catching certain species of fish, such as *Leptoscarus vaigiensis* (*Komokomo*) and *Stegastes fasciolatus* (*Nganga*).
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The plant is also known by the common names **candleberry**, **Indian walnut**, ***kemiri***, **varnish tree**, ***nuez de la India***, ***buah keras***, ***godou***, **kukui tree**, and ***rata kekuna***.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] It became Proto-Eastern-Malayo-Polynesian and Proto-Oceanic **tuRi* which is then reduplicated.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Modern cognates including Fijian, Tongan, Rarotongan, and Niue *tui-tui*; and Hawaiian *kui-kui* or *kukui*.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] The Malay language in both has another name given to the nut which is *buah keras* (literally "hard fruit").
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Uganda, the seed is referred to as *kabakanjagala*, meaning "the king loves me".
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] In Maui, the *kukui* is a symbol of enlightenment, protection, and peace.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] Kamapuaʻa, the hog-man fertility demigod, was said to be able to transform into a *kukui* tree.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] One of the legends told of Kamapuaʻa: one day, a man beat his wife to death and buried her beneath Kamapuaʻa while he was in tree form.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] *Kukui* was named the state tree of Hawaii on 1 May 1959 due to its multitude of uses.
[src:breadfruit/aleurites-moluccanus] It also represents the island of Molokaʻi, whose symbolic color is the silvery green of the *kukui* leaf.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] In chemistry, an **alkali** (/ˈælkəlaɪ/ ⓘ; from the Arabic word *al-qaly*, القالِي "saltwort") also **base** is a hydroxide of any of either the alkali metal which are Group I s-block elements, or the alkaline earth metal which are Group II s-block.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] *Alkali* can also be defined as a base that dissolves in water.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] A solution of a soluble base has a pH greater than 7.0.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] The adjectives ***alkaline*** and, less often, ***alkalescent*** are commonly used in English as a synonyms for *basic*, especially for bases soluble in water.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] This broad use of the term is likely to have come about because alkalis were the first bases known to obey the Arrhenius definition of a base, and they are still among the most common bases.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] The word *alkali* is derived from Arabic *al qalīy* (or *alkali*), meaning 'the calcined ashes' (see calcination), referring to the original source of alkaline substances.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] A water-extract of burned plant ashes, called *potash* and composed mostly of potassium carbonate, was mildly basic.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] After heating this substance with calcium hydroxide (*slaked lime*), a far more strongly basic substance known as *caustic potash* (potassium hydroxide) was produced.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] Caustic potash was traditionally used in conjunction with animal fats to produce soft soaps, one of the caustic processes that rendered soaps from fats in the process of saponification, one known since antiquity.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] Plant potash lent the name to the element potassium, which was first derived from caustic potash, and also gave potassium its chemical symbol **K** (from the German name *Kalium*), which ultimately derived from al**k**ali.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] Alkalis are all Arrhenius bases, ones which form hydroxide ions (OH−) when dissolved in water.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] The terms "base" and "alkali" are often used interchangeably, particularly outside the context of chemistry and chemical engineering.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] There are various, more specific definitions for the concept of an alkali.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] Alkalis are usually defined as a subset of the bases.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] The second subset of bases is also called an "Arrhenius base".
[src:breadfruit/alkali] Soils with pH values that are higher than 7.3 are usually defined as being alkaline.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] These soils can occur naturally due to the presence of alkali salts.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] Although many plants do prefer slightly basic soil (including vegetables like cabbage and fodder like buffalo grass), most plants prefer mildly acidic soil (with pHs between 6.0 and 6.8), and alkaline soils can cause problems.
[src:breadfruit/alkali] In alkali lakes (also called *soda lakes*), evaporation concentrates the naturally occurring carbonate salts, giving rise to an alkalic and often saline lake.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit was spread into Oceania via the Austronesian expansion and is believed to have been selectively bred in Polynesia from the breadnut (*Artocarpus camansi*).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] British and French navigators introduced a few Polynesian seedless varieties to Caribbean islands during the late 18th century.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Today it is widely grown in tropical regions throughout South and Southeast Asia, islands in the Pacific Ocean and Caribbean Sea, lowland Central America, northern South America and Africa.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In addition to the fruit serving as a staple food in many cultures, the light, sturdy timber of breadfruit has been used for making furniture, houses, and surfboards.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is also closely related to the jackfruit.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit trees grow to a height of 26 m (85 ft).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The large and thick leaves are deeply cut into pinnate lobes.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] All parts of the tree yield latex, which is useful for boat caulking.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The trees are monoecious, with male and female flowers growing on the same tree.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The male flowers emerge first, followed shortly afterward by the female flowers.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The latter grow into capitula, which are capable of pollination just three days later.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Pollination occurs mainly by fruit bats, but cultivated varieties produce fruit without pollination.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The compound, false fruit develops from the swollen perianth, and originates from 1,500 to 2,000 flowers visible on the skin of the fruit as hexagon-like disks.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is one of the highest-yielding food plants, with a single tree producing up to 200 or more grapefruit-sized fruits per season, requiring limited care.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In the South Pacific, the trees yield 50 to 150 fruits per year, usually round, oval, or oblong, and weighing 0.25 to 6.0 kg (0.55 to 13 lb).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Productivity varies between wet and dry areas.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Studies in Barbados indicate a reasonable potential of 15 to 30 t/ha (6.7 to 13.4 short ton/acre).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The ovoid fruit has a rough surface, and each fruit is divided into many achenes, each surrounded by a fleshy perianth and growing on a fleshy receptacle.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Most selectively bred cultivars have seedless fruit, whereas seeded varieties are grown mainly for their edible seeds.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is usually propagated using root cuttings.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is closely related to the breadnut.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is similar in appearance to its relative of the same genus, the jackfruit (*Artocarpus heterophyllus*).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The closely related *Artocarpus camansi* can be distinguished from *A. altilis* by having spinier fruits with numerous seeds.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] *Artocarpus mariannensis* can be distinguished by having dark green, elongated fruits with darker yellow flesh, as well as entire or shallowly lobed leaves.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is propagated mainly by seeds, though seedless breadfruit can be propagated by transplanting suckers that grow off the surface roots of the tree.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The roots can be purposefully injured to induce the growth of suckers, which are then separated from the root and planted in a pot or directly transplanted into the ground.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Sucker cuttings are placed in plastic bags containing a mixture of soil, peat, and sand, and kept in the shade while moistened with liquid fertilizer.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] When roots are developed, the transplant is put in full sun until time for planting in the orchard.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] For large-scale propagation, root cuttings are preferred, using segments about 10 cm (2 in) thick and 20 cm (9 in) long.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Rooting may take up to 5 months to develop, with the young trees ready for planting when they are 60 cm (2 ft) high.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The term "breadfruit" was first used in the 17th century to describe the bread-like texture of the fruit when baked.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit has hundreds of varieties and numerous common names varying by its geographic distribution.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] According to DNA fingerprinting studies, the seeded wild ancestor of breadfruit is the breadnut (*A. camansi*), which is native to New Guinea, the Maluku Islands, and the Philippines.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit was one of the canoe plants spread by Austronesian voyagers around 3,000 years ago into Micronesia, Melanesia, and Polynesia, where it was not native.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is an equatorial, lowland species.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It has been spread from its Pacific source to many tropical regions.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In 1769, Joseph Banks was stationed in Tahiti as part of the *Endeavour* expedition commanded by Captain James Cook.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The late-18th-century quest for cheap, high-energy food sources for slaves in British colonies prompted colonial administrators and plantation owners to call for breadfruit to be brought to the Caribbean.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] As president of the Royal Society, Banks provided a cash bounty and gold medal for success in this endeavor and successfully lobbied for a British Naval expedition.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] After an unsuccessful voyage to the South Pacific to collect the plants as commander of HMS *Bounty*, in 1791, William Bligh commanded a second expedition with *Providence* and *Assistant*, which collected seedless breadfruit plants in Tahiti and transported these to St.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The plant grows best at elevations below 650 m (2,130 ft), but is found at elevations of 1,550 m (5,090 ft).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Its preferred soils are neutral to alkaline (pH of 6.1–7.4) and either sand, sandy loam, loam, or sandy clay loam.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is able to grow in coral sands and saline soils.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The breadfruit is ultra-tropical, requiring a temperature range of 16–38 °C (61–100 °F) and an annual rainfall of 2,000–2,500 mm (80–100 in).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is 71% water, 27% carbohydrates, and 1% protein, and contains negligible fat (table).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw breadfruit supplies 103 calories, is a rich source of vitamin C (32% of the Daily Value, DV), and provides a moderate source of potassium (16% DV), with no other nutrients in significant content.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is a staple food in many tropical regions.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Most breadfruit varieties produce fruit throughout the year.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Both ripe and unripe fruit have culinary uses; unripe breadfruit is cooked before consumption.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Before being eaten, the fruit is roasted, baked, fried, or boiled.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] When cooked, the taste of moderately ripe breadfruit is described as potato-like, or similar to freshly baked bread.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] One breadfruit tree can produce 200 kilograms (450 lb) each season.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Because breadfruit trees usually produce large crops at certain times of the year, the preservation of harvested fruit is an issue.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] One traditional preservation technique known throughout Oceania is to bury peeled and washed fruits in a leaf-lined pit, where they ferment over several weeks and produce a sour, sticky paste (*masi* in Samoa and Tonga, *māhi* in Tahiti, *mā* in the Carolines).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Stored in this way, the product may endure a year or more.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Some pits are reported to have produced edible contents more than 20 years after burial.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Remnants of pit-like formations with stone scattered around (presumed to line them) are often clues indicating prehistoric settlement to archaeologists studying precontact history of French Polynesia.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In addition to being edible raw, breadfruit can be dried and ground into flour and the seeds can be cooked for consumption.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The seedless breadfruit is found in Brunei, Indonesia, and Malaysia, where it is called *sukun*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is commonly made into fritters and eaten as snacks.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit fritters are sold as local street food.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In the Philippines, breadfruit is known as *rimas* in Tagalog and *kolo* in the Visayan languages.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is also called *kamansi* (also spelled *camansi*), along with the closely related *Artocarpus camansi*, and the endemic *Artocarpus blancoi* (*tipolo* or *antipolo*).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] All three species, as well as the closely related jackfruit, are commonly used much in the same way in savory dishes.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The immature fruits are most commonly eaten as *ginataang rimas* (cooked with coconut milk).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In the Hawaiian staple food called *poi*, the traditional ingredient of mashed taro root can be replaced by, or augmented with, mashed breadfruit (*ʻulu* in Hawaiian).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The resulting "breadfruit poi" is called *poi ʻulu*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In India, fritters of breadfruit, called *paatponnos/nirponnos* in Kannada it's called *Jeegujje* or "Deevihalasu" in Konkani or *kadachakka varuthath* in Malayalam, are a local delicacy in coastal Goa, Karnataka and Kerala.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Seychelles, it was traditionally eaten as a substitute for rice, as an accompaniment to the mains.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It would either be consumed boiled (*friyapen bwi*) or grilled (*friyapen griye*), where it would be put whole in the wood fire used for cooking the main meal and then taken out when ready.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is also eaten as a dessert, called *ladob friyapen*, where it is boiled in coconut milk, sugar, vanilla, cinnamon, and a pinch of salt.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Sri Lanka, it is cooked as a curry using coconut milk and spices (which becomes a side dish) or boiled.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Boiled breadfruit is a famous main meal.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is often consumed with scraped coconut or *coconut sambol*, made of scraped coconut, red chili powder, and salt mixed with a dash of lime juice.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] A traditional sweet snack made of finely sliced, sun-dried breadfruit chips deep-fried in coconut oil and dipped in heated treacle or sugar syrup is known as *rata del petti*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Belize, the Mayan people call it *masapan*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Puerto Rico, breadfruit is called *mapén*, *panapén* or *pana*, for short, although the name *pana* is often used to refer to breadnut, seeds of which have traditionally been boiled, peeled, and eaten whole.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In some inland regions, it is also called *mapén* and used to make *pasteles* and *alcapurrias*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is often served boiled with a mixture of sauteed *bacalao* (salted cod fish), olive oil, and onions, mostly as *tostones* where about 1-inch chunks are fried, lighty flattened, and fried again.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] *Mofongo de panapén* is fried breadfruit mashed with olive oil, garlic, broth, and *chicharrón*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] *Rellenos de panapén* is the breadfruit version of *papa rellena*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Dipping sauce can be made from boiled, ripe breadfruit, similar to chutney, using spices, sesame seeds, herbs, lentil, coconut milk, and fruit.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Both ripe and unripe fruit are boiled together and mashed with milk and butter to make *pastelón de panapén*, a dish similar to lasagna.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Ripe breadfruit is used in desserts, including *flan de pana* (breadfruit custard).
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] *Cazuela* is a crustless pie with ripe breadfruit, spices, raisins, coconut milk, and sweet potatoes.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit flour is sold all over Puerto Rico and used for making bread, pastries, cookies, pancakes, waffles, crepes, and *almojábana*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] A *Breadfruit Festival* in which traditional and novel breadfruit-based dishes are sold is celebrated on the last Friday of August in Barrio Mariana, Humacao, Puerto Rico.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In the Dominican Republic, it is called *buen pan* or "good bread".
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit is not popular in Dominican cookery and is used mainly for feeding pigs.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Barbados, breadfruit is boiled with salted meat and mashed with butter to make breadfruit coucou.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is usually eaten with saucy meat dishes.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Haiti, steamed breadfruit is mashed to make a dish called *tonmtonm* which is eaten with a sauce made with okra and other ingredients, such as fish and crab.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Trinidad and Tobago, breadfruit is boiled, then fried and eaten with saucy meat dishes like curried duck.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] In Jamaica, breadfruit is boiled in soups or roasted on stove top, in the oven or on wood coal.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is eaten with the national dish ackee and salt fish.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The ripe fruit is used in salads or fried as a side dish.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Vincent and the Grenadines, it is eaten boiled in soups, roasted, and fried.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Roasted breadfruit, served with fried jackfish, is the country's national dish.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The ripe fruit is used as a base to make drinks, cakes, and ice cream.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit was widely used in a variety of ways among Pacific Islanders.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Its lightweight wood (specific gravity of 0.27) is resistant to termites and shipworms, so it is used as timber for structures and outrigger canoes.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Its wood pulp can also be used to make paper, called breadfruit *tapa*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The wood of the breadfruit tree was one of the most valuable timbers in the construction of traditional houses in Samoan architecture.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit contains phytochemicals having potential as an insect repellent.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The parts of the fruits that are discarded can be used to feed livestock.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The leaves of breadfruit trees can also be browsed by cattle.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Breadfruit, however, exudes latex upon harvesting, causing the plant sap to adhere to the surface, leading to the staining of the epicarp.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Proper methods of breadfruit harvesting usually include the process of draining the latex and disposing of it.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Sticky white sap or latex is present in all parts of the breadfruit tree and has been used for glue, caulk, and even chewing gum.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Native Hawaiians used its sticky latex to trap birds, whose feathers were made into cloaks.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] On Puluwat in the Caroline Islands, in the context of sacred *yitang* lore, breadfruit (*poi*) is a figure of speech for knowledge.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] This lore is organized into five categories: war, magic, meetings, navigation, and *breadfruit*.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] According to an etiological Hawaiian myth, the breadfruit originated from the sacrifice of the war god Kū.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] After deciding to live secretly among mortals as a farmer, Kū married and had children.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] He and his family lived happily until a famine seized their island.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] When he could no longer bear to watch his children suffer, Kū told his wife that he could deliver them from starvation, but to do so he would have to leave them.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Reluctantly she agreed, and at her word, Kū descended into the ground right where he had stood until only the top of his head was visible.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] His family waited around the spot he had last been, day and night, watering it with their tears until suddenly, a small green shoot appeared where Kū had stood.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Quickly, the shoot grew into a tall and leafy tree that was laden with heavy breadfruits that Kū's family and neighbors gratefully ate, joyfully saved from starvation.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Many breadfruit hybrids and cultivars are widely distributed throughout the Pacific though they are seedless or otherwise biologically incapable of naturally dispersing long distances.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] It is therefore clear that humans aided distribution of the plant in the Pacific, specifically prehistoric groups who colonized the Pacific Islands.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] To investigate the patterns of human migration throughout the Pacific, scientists have used molecular dating of breadfruit hybrids and cultivars in concert with anthropological data.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] Results support the west-to-east migration hypothesis, in which the Lapita people are thought to have traveled from Melanesia to numerous Polynesian islands.
[src:breadfruit/breadfruit] The world's largest collection of breadfruit varieties was established by botanist Diane Ragone, from over 20 years' travel to 50 Pacific islands, on a 4-hectare (10-acre) plot outside of Hana, on the isolated east coast of Maui (Hawaii).
